               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17890225-31-person371">
                  RICHARD
                   HANSET
               <interp inst="t17890225-31-person371" type="surname" value="HANSET"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17890225-31-person371" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17890225-31-person371" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a green-grocer; on Saturday the 3d of January last, between 11 and 12 in the forenoon; I was standing at my door; I saw the prisoner go into Mr. Forbes's shop, he staid there about a minute and a half, and he brought out this dressing-glass with him; he went by me with the glass; I went into the shop, and asked Mrs. Forbes, if she had let any body have a glass? she said she had not; I pursued him, and took him with the glass on him, and he was committed; the glass was delivered to the constable.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17890225-31-person372">
                  ROBERT
                   HATCH
               <interp inst="t17890225-31-person372" type="surname" value="HATCH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17890225-31-person372" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17890225-31-person372" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a constable; I received this glass from Mr. Forbes; I have had it ever since; the prosecutor marked it.</p>
               <p>(The glass deposed to by the prosecutor.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I have nothing to say.</p>
               <p>
